A binary tree can be uniquely constructed only when one traversal is Inorder and the other is either Preorder or Postorder.
Why?

Inorder tells us how nodes are split into left and right subtrees.
Preorder/Postorder tells us the root.

Shorter version--> return (a != b) && (a == 2 || b == 2);

or

class Solution{	
	public:	
		bool uniqueBinaryTree(int a, int b){
           if(a == b) return false;
           if((a == 1 && b == 3) || (a == 3 && b == 1))
           return false;

return true;		}
};
